# -*- encoding: utf-8 -*-
# Arc: WarriorPath | Scene: WarriorRahayal1
# Source: C:\Program Files (x86)\Steam\steamapps\common\The Survival of Sarah Rose\game\script.rpy

translate ru strings:

    old "Leaving the desert, they travelled along with the the rest of the Mythran army."
    new "Leaving the desert, they travelled along with the the rest of the Mythran army."

    old "Well supplied and guided by the skilled navigators of the Mythran Empire, they faced little dangers from the desert."
    new "Well supplied and guided by the skilled navigators of the Mythran Empire, they faced little dangers from the desert."

    old "When they passed by Bagrad on their return, the city was quiet."
    new "When they passed by Bagrad on their return, the city was quiet."

    old "The gates of the once great city had been closed."
    new "The gates of the once great city had been closed."

    old "A few plumes of smoke rose up, suggesting at least some still lived there."
    new "A few plumes of smoke rose up, suggesting at least some still lived there."

    old "But nobody left the city. They saw no movement on the walls."
    new "But nobody left the city. They saw no movement on the walls."

    old "There was no reason for them to return to the city again. All that could be looted, had been."
    new "There was no reason for them to return to the city again. All that could be looted, had been."

    old "Sarah doubted there would even be any food or water left in the city. Not enough to supply an army."
    new "Sarah doubted there would even be any food or water left in the city. Not enough to supply an army."

    old "Regardless, they now had the Mythran stock, and so they wanted for neither food nor drink."
    new "Regardless, they now had the Mythran stock, and so they wanted for neither food nor drink."

    old "And, their army passed by silent Bagrad, now more tomb than city."
    new "And, their army passed by silent Bagrad, now more tomb than city."

    old "Continuing to make good time, it wasn't more than two weeks before they had finally left the deserts behind."
    new "Continuing to make good time, it wasn't more than two weeks before they had finally left the deserts behind."

    old "The endless dunes gradually gave way for fields of grass."
    new "The endless dunes gradually gave way for fields of grass."

    old "Sticking to the road, they soon began to see the first signs of civilization again."
    new "Sticking to the road, they soon began to see the first signs of civilization again."

    old "Out here, there were mostly farmer towns."
    new "Out here, there were mostly farmer towns."

    old "Small villages that worked the fields, far away from any real authorities."
    new "Small villages that worked the fields, far away from any real authorities."

    old "For the most part, they simple worked the fields and ate what they grew."
    new "For the most part, they simple worked the fields and ate what they grew."

    old "When the winters were harsh, they suffered. When the summers were easy, they prospered."
    new "When the winters were harsh, they suffered. When the summers were easy, they prospered."

    old "Only nature was the real enemy out here."
    new "Only nature was the real enemy out here."

    old "A passing army drew some attention, but they were a curiosity to the people here."
    new "A passing army drew some attention, but they were a curiosity to the people here."

    old "They knew that for the most part, their poverty protected them from any real looting."
    new "They knew that for the most part, their poverty protected them from any real looting."

    old "Mostly. There was always the occasional crime."
    new "Mostly. There was always the occasional crime."

    old "They continued along the road for several more days, before finally coming upon the village of Hillstown."
    new "They continued along the road for several more days, before finally coming upon the village of Hillstown."

    old "Passing over the bridge, the Mythrans and Sarah's own army marched into the town."
    new "Passing over the bridge, the Mythrans and Sarah's own army marched into the town."

    old "It wasn't much, certainly not compared to the great cities of the world such as Lethram and Rahayal, but it was more than they had seen in a long time."
    new "It wasn't much, certainly not compared to the great cities of the world such as Lethram and Rahayal, but it was more than they had seen in a long time."

    old "It was the very first town large enough for them to rest in."
    new "It was the very first town large enough for them to rest in."

    old "Enough food and drink to offer some distraction from the usual rations."
    new "Enough food and drink to offer some distraction from the usual rations."

    old "Enough women to keep the soldiers from fighting amongst themselves."
    new "Enough women to keep the soldiers from fighting amongst themselves."

    old "As her forces marched into town, the soldiers began to fan out, searching for places to sleep. Either outside, or if they were lucky, under a roof."
    new "As her forces marched into town, the soldiers began to fan out, searching for places to sleep. Either outside, or if they were lucky, under a roof."

    old "If the villagers had a problem with it, none spoke up."
    new "If the villagers had a problem with it, none spoke up."

    old "Sarah doubted they would, even if they did."
    new "Sarah doubted they would, even if they did."

    old "Half of what kept them in line was the fear, the other half the money that the soldiers freely spend."
    new "Half of what kept them in line was the fear, the other half the money that the soldiers freely spend."

    old "The sun was setting as Sarah looked out over the town square."
    new "The sun was setting as Sarah looked out over the town square."

    old "Already, soldiers and locals had begun to mingle."
    new "Already, soldiers and locals had begun to mingle."

    old "Samayra came running up to her. A large pile of scrolls under her arm."
    new "Samayra came running up to her. A large pile of scrolls under her arm."

    old "I told you, Samayra, you don't have to call me that."
    new "I told you, Samayra, you don't have to call me that."

    old "Samayra did her best to perform a salute without dropping anything."
    new "Samayra did her best to perform a salute without dropping anything."

    old "Do you prefer boss?"
    new "Do you prefer boss?"

    old "That somehow sounds even worse."
    new "That somehow sounds even worse."

    old "Samayra had taken to her new role as Sarah's secretary with great zeal."
    new "Samayra had taken to her new role as Sarah's secretary with great zeal."

    old "Before long, Sarah began to realize how much of her daily paperwork had dissapeared."
    new "Before long, Sarah began to realize how much of her daily paperwork had dissapeared."

    old "What had once been piles of scattered daily reports about the status of food or money, instead became one simple and clean report."
    new "What had once been piles of scattered daily reports about the status of food or money, instead became one simple and clean report."

    old "Sarah had even seen sides of Samayra she had never expected."
    new "Sarah had even seen sides of Samayra she had never expected."

    old "Once she heard her shouting at a poor soldier that had failed to submit the proper paperwork a third time in a row."
    new "Once she heard her shouting at a poor soldier that had failed to submit the proper paperwork a third time in a row."

    old "Sarah was happy. Happy that so much of the paperwork was gone, but also that Samayra seemed to find some purpose in the role."
    new "Sarah was happy. Happy that so much of the paperwork was gone, but also that Samayra seemed to find some purpose in the role."

    old "I've come to deliver the daily report."
    new "I've come to deliver the daily report."

    old "Sarah took the single sheet of paper from Samayra."
    new "Sarah took the single sheet of paper from Samayra."

    old "She looked it over."
    new "She looked it over."

    old "Looks about right."
    new "Looks about right."

    old "Samayra nodded."
    new "Samayra nodded."

    old "Food supplies have gone down by a bit, but I hope we can stock up a little here."
    new "Food supplies have gone down by a bit, but I hope we can stock up a little here."

    old "We can always just ask the Mythrans to share more."
    new "We can always just ask the Mythrans to share more."

    old "Sure, but best we don't become dependent on them, right?"
    new "Sure, but best we don't become dependent on them, right?"

    old "When did you become the cynical one?"
    new "When did you become the cynical one?"

    old "Samayra blushed."
    new "Samayra blushed."

    old "W-w-whatever! I just need you to sign here, so I have the authority to spend funds on purchasing food!"
    new "W-w-whatever! I just need you to sign here, so I have the authority to spend funds on purchasing food!"

    old "Sarah continued to laugh as she grabbed the sheet of paper and quickly signed it."
    new "Sarah continued to laugh as she grabbed the sheet of paper and quickly signed it."

    old "She handed it back to Samayra."
    new "She handed it back to Samayra."

    old "She saw Samayra make a move to leave."
    new "She saw Samayra make a move to leave."

    old "What? Don't you want to stay and talk?"
    new "What? Don't you want to stay and talk?"

    old "No time! It's so busy! I have a thousand things to do!"
    new "No time! It's so busy! I have a thousand things to do!"

    old "The girl actually seemed flustered."
    new "The girl actually seemed flustered."

    old "Unless you want to talk, of course!"
    new "Unless you want to talk, of course!"

    old "Sarah laughed and waved her hands."
    new "Sarah laughed and waved her hands."

    old "There would be other times to talk to the girl, and she feared she might add more stress for no reason."
    new "There would be other times to talk to the girl, and she feared she might add more stress for no reason."

    old "Don't worry about be, you can go back to your work."
    new "Don't worry about be, you can go back to your work."

    old "Samayra attempted another salute."
    new "Samayra attempted another salute."

    old "Thanks, boss!"
    new "Thanks, boss!"

    old "Samayra took off in a sprint."
    new "Samayra took off in a sprint."

    old "Don't call me that!"
    new "Don't call me that!"

    old "Sarah only heard Samayra laugh as she continued to run."
    new "Sarah only heard Samayra laugh as she continued to run."

    old "Leaning up against a wall, Sarah continued to watch all the people buzz about."
    new "Leaning up against a wall, Sarah continued to watch all the people buzz about."

    old "It was still strange to her to consider that she had an army of her own."
    new "It was still strange to her to consider that she had an army of her own."

    old "For so long she'd followed Vaelen's command. Now there was nobody else to look at to lead."
    new "For so long she'd followed Vaelen's command. Now there was nobody else to look at to lead."

    old "It felt free. But along with the freedom, a fear. She could no longer push her own responsibility onto another."
    new "It felt free. But along with the freedom, a fear. She could no longer push her own responsibility onto another."

    old "Her choices were her own. As were the consequences."
    new "Her choices were her own. As were the consequences."

    old "Sarah saw Kate walk up."
    new "Sarah saw Kate walk up."

    old "Let's hope there's going to be a town left after tonight."
    new "Let's hope there's going to be a town left after tonight."

    old "You think the men will be causing trouble?"
    new "You think the men will be causing trouble?"

    old "Nothing the town can't handle."
    new "Nothing the town can't handle."

    old "Might be a whole lot more kids running about nine-months from now."
    new "Might be a whole lot more kids running about nine-months from now."

    old "It wasn't untrue."
    new "It wasn't untrue."

    old "Soldiers were fit. They had money. And for most of the women in town, they were the first men they'd seen that they hadn't grown up with."
    new "Soldiers were fit. They had money. And for most of the women in town, they were the first men they'd seen that they hadn't grown up with."

    old "All together, it made things rather easy."
    new "All together, it made things rather easy."

    old "Some might have a bastard. Just as many would likely quickly marry a local boy and pin the birth on him."
    new "Some might have a bastard. Just as many would likely quickly marry a local boy and pin the birth on him."

    old "And what of it, thought Sarah."
    new "And what of it, thought Sarah."

    old "Most women here ended up having a dozen children or so."
    new "Most women here ended up having a dozen children or so."

    old "One-different-from-the-others, a rounding error on the whole of it."
    new "One-different-from-the-others, a rounding error on the whole of it."

    old "It was one way to live a life, she thought to herself."
    new "It was one way to live a life, she thought to herself."

    old "What about you?"
    new "What about you?"

    old "You up to any trouble?"
    new "You up to any trouble?"

    old "You know I'm always on good behavior."
    new "You know I'm always on good behavior."

    old "Want to get a drink with me later?"
    new "Want to get a drink with me later?"

    old "I'd really like to, but I promised my own men I'd hang out with them."
    new "I'd really like to, but I promised my own men I'd hang out with them."

    old "Besides, I can't be seen hanging about you too much you know. They're going to start thinking I'm your favorite."
    new "Besides, I can't be seen hanging about you too much you know. They're going to start thinking I'm your favorite."

    old "Maybe you are my favorite."
    new "Maybe you are my favorite."

    old "Ooh, definitely, but I don't want them to know that."
    new "Ooh, definitely, but I don't want them to know that."

    old "Kate laughed as she began to walk away."
    new "Kate laughed as she began to walk away."

    old "As night fell and Sarah was far from tired, she entered the one tavern that the city had."
    new "As night fell and Sarah was far from tired, she entered the one tavern that the city had."

    old "It wasn't much, but it would do."
    new "It wasn't much, but it would do."

    old "All around the hearth and throughout the room, Sarah saw soldiers drinking."
    new "All around the hearth and throughout the room, Sarah saw soldiers drinking."

    old "A few greeted her, many more were already too deep into their drinks."
    new "A few greeted her, many more were already too deep into their drinks."

    old "Sarah grabbed a pitcher of beer and sat in the corner."
    new "Sarah grabbed a pitcher of beer and sat in the corner."

    old "Watching from here, she could see the dynamics of the crowd unfold."
    new "Watching from here, she could see the dynamics of the crowd unfold."

    old "The way her own men, the Mythrans and the villagers all socialized."
    new "The way her own men, the Mythrans and the villagers all socialized."

    old "Nursing her drink, the hours quickly passed, and before long, Sarah could feel herself grow drowsy."
    new "Nursing her drink, the hours quickly passed, and before long, Sarah could feel herself grow drowsy."

    old "Pushing herself up to her feet, she had all but intended to find a place to sleep when the door to the tavern was suddenly thrown open."
    new "Pushing herself up to her feet, she had all but intended to find a place to sleep when the door to the tavern was suddenly thrown open."

    old "A large, burly man stormed into the room. The town blacksmith, perhaps, Sarah thought by his appearance."
    new "A large, burly man stormed into the room. The town blacksmith, perhaps, Sarah thought by his appearance."

    old "Help!!!"
    new "Help!!!"

    old "His deep voice, filled with panic, cut through the room."
    new "His deep voice, filled with panic, cut through the room."

    old "All went quiet."
    new "All went quiet."

    old "Gods! Help me, please! Hurry!"
    new "Gods! Help me, please! Hurry!"

    old "Sarah rushed forward, seizing control of the situation."
    new "Sarah rushed forward, seizing control of the situation."

    old "Calm down!"
    new "Calm down!"

    old "Tell me what is going on here."
    new "Tell me what is going on here."

    old "Please! You have to help us!"
    new "Please! You have to help us!"

    old "Help you?"
    new "Help you?"

    old "It attacked again! That poor girl from the Miller family!"
    new "It attacked again! That poor girl from the Miller family!"

    old "The Beast! The Beast!"
    new "The Beast! The Beast!"

    old "The man continued to yell, his speech becoming more incoherent with every word."
    new "The man continued to yell, his speech becoming more incoherent with every word."

    old "Suddenly, more people came running into the tavern."
    new "Suddenly, more people came running into the tavern."

    old "Among them, one was dressed in finer things than most."
    new "Among them, one was dressed in finer things than most."

    old "The man pushed himself to the front."
    new "The man pushed himself to the front."

    old "Bring her in here!"
    new "Bring her in here!"

    old "Sarah watched from the side as several soldiers came into the tavern, covered in blood."
    new "Sarah watched from the side as several soldiers came into the tavern, covered in blood."

    old "Carried between them, a young woman, bleeding from her hip."
    new "Carried between them, a young woman, bleeding from her hip."

    old "She had lost so much blood, her gown was nearly all red, sticking to her body."
    new "She had lost so much blood, her gown was nearly all red, sticking to her body."

    old "Her already fair skin had turned nearly entirely white."
    new "Her already fair skin had turned nearly entirely white."

    old "If she was awake or alive, she gave little hint of it."
    new "If she was awake or alive, she gave little hint of it."

    old "Put her down on the table!"
    new "Put her down on the table!"

    old "The men placed the woman on the table."
    new "The men placed the woman on the table."

    old "Get my tools and supplies from my house, they're in the living room! Hurry!"
    new "Get my tools and supplies from my house, they're in the living room! Hurry!"

    old "A man ran out and soon returned with the tools that had been requested."
    new "A man ran out and soon returned with the tools that had been requested."

    old "The Mayor rolled up his sleeves and pulled the tools from the bag."
    new "The Mayor rolled up his sleeves and pulled the tools from the bag."

    old "Hold her arms and legs down. We don't want her to move."
    new "Hold her arms and legs down. We don't want her to move."

    old "The soldiers did as instructed, pinning the weakened woman down onto the surface of the table."
    new "The soldiers did as instructed, pinning the weakened woman down onto the surface of the table."

    old "As the scene unfolded, Sarah, much like everyone else, was quiet and only watched."
    new "As the scene unfolded, Sarah, much like everyone else, was quiet and only watched."

    old "They were soldiers. Inflicting wounds was easy to them. Fixing wounds was a more delicate skill."
    new "They were soldiers. Inflicting wounds was easy to them. Fixing wounds was a more delicate skill."

    old "The Mayor's hands moved with a swift and practiced ease."
    new "The Mayor's hands moved with a swift and practiced ease."

    old "Pulling out scalpels, iron tongs and many more instruments, he began to operate on the woman."
    new "Pulling out scalpels, iron tongs and many more instruments, he began to operate on the woman."

    old "Weakened as she was, she offered little resistance to the strong soldiers that held her down."
    new "Weakened as she was, she offered little resistance to the strong soldiers that held her down."

    old "As her cries of pain grew louder, they stuffed a wooden rod between her teeth to keep her down."
    new "As her cries of pain grew louder, they stuffed a wooden rod between her teeth to keep her down."

    old "All the while, the mayor kept moving, his hands swiftly changing one instrument for the next."
    new "All the while, the mayor kept moving, his hands swiftly changing one instrument for the next."

    old "Finally, when all was done, he began to stitch the woman's sides up."
    new "Finally, when all was done, he began to stitch the woman's sides up."

    old "When he pulled away the dress, drenched with blood, Sarah saw a brief moment of the young woman's skin."
    new "When he pulled away the dress, drenched with blood, Sarah saw a brief moment of the young woman's skin."

    old "At least what was left of it."
    new "At least what was left of it."

    old "A vicious wound could be seen on her hips."
    new "A vicious wound could be seen on her hips."

    old "Oddly, Sarah found herself breathing a sigh of relief."
    new "Oddly, Sarah found herself breathing a sigh of relief."

    old "That was the not the wound that a soldier might have given her. It was more like something a wild animal might do."
    new "That was the not the wound that a soldier might have given her. It was more like something a wild animal might do."

    old "She had feared that one of her soldiers might have been the cause of all this carnage."
    new "She had feared that one of her soldiers might have been the cause of all this carnage."

    old "The Mayor sighed as he finished stitching up the girl."
    new "The Mayor sighed as he finished stitching up the girl."

    old "Take her to the recovery house and give her an entire cup of shade-tea."
    new "Take her to the recovery house and give her an entire cup of shade-tea."

    old "What if she cannot drink?"
    new "What if she cannot drink?"

    old "Then you pry open her mouth and force it down her throat if you have to."
    new "Then you pry open her mouth and force it down her throat if you have to."

    old "She might live, she might not, but if she doesn't drink some shade-tea, she'll be dead for certain."
    new "She might live, she might not, but if she doesn't drink some shade-tea, she'll be dead for certain."

    old "Yes sir!"
    new "Yes sir!"

    old "The soldiers gathered up the woman and carried her out as gently as they could."
    new "The soldiers gathered up the woman and carried her out as gently as they could."

    old "Blood still stained the table."
    new "Blood still stained the table."

    old "Most of the other soldiers slowly exited the tavern as well."
    new "Most of the other soldiers slowly exited the tavern as well."

    old "Whatever the mood had been, the bloodshed had soured it."
    new "Whatever the mood had been, the bloodshed had soured it."

    old "Sarah saw the Mayor sitting by himself in a corner, trying to recover."
    new "Sarah saw the Mayor sitting by himself in a corner, trying to recover."

    old "What happened?"
    new "What happened?"

    old "He looked at her, stunned."
    new "He looked at her, stunned."

    old "Sarah. I'm the head of the mercenary company."
    new "Sarah. I'm the head of the mercenary company."

    old "He shook her head."
    new "He shook her head."

    old "I was expecting a man."
    new "I was expecting a man."

    old "I've heard that before."
    new "I've heard that before."

    old "She gestured at the table."
    new "She gestured at the table."

    old "Who did that to that woman?"
    new "Who did that to that woman?"

    old "The Mayor burried his head in his hands."
    new "The Mayor burried his head in his hands."

    old "Who? More like what."
    new "Who? More like what."

    old "It has been plaguing us for months now..."
    new "It has been plaguing us for months now..."

    old "You mean this has happened before?"
    new "You mean this has happened before?"

    old "The Mayor nodded."
    new "The Mayor nodded."

    old "It started about half a year ago...the first attack I mean."
    new "It started about half a year ago...the first attack I mean."

    old "A young girl had snuck out of her parent's house to pick moonflowers in the night."
    new "A young girl had snuck out of her parent's house to pick moonflowers in the night."

    old "She came back screaming into town, claw marks along her back, bleeding."
    new "She came back screaming into town, claw marks along her back, bleeding."

    old "Back then we thought it had been a wolf of some kind. Not common, but also not unheard of in these parts."
    new "Back then we thought it had been a wolf of some kind. Not common, but also not unheard of in these parts."

    old "But then a few weeks later, another attack."
    new "But then a few weeks later, another attack."

    old "That time it was one of the carpenter's apprentices. Boy lost his entire left hand but at least he lived to tell about it."
    new "That time it was one of the carpenter's apprentices. Boy lost his entire left hand but at least he lived to tell about it."

    old "After, the attacks became more frequent and grew more violent."
    new "After, the attacks became more frequent and grew more violent."

    old "We couldn't deny something was going on."
    new "We couldn't deny something was going on."

    old "Sarah leaned up against the wall."
    new "Sarah leaned up against the wall."

    old "The blacksmith said it was a beast...the injury, it looked like something a wild animal might inflict. Is that what this is?"
    new "The blacksmith said it was a beast...the injury, it looked like something a wild animal might inflict. Is that what this is?"

    old "The Mayor's shoulders fell lower as he leaned forward."
    new "The Mayor's shoulders fell lower as he leaned forward."

    old "It strikes at night, and there are some confusing reports. It's big, we know that much."
    new "It strikes at night, and there are some confusing reports. It's big, we know that much."

    old "Most describe it as something between a wolf or a bear, but nobody ever really seems to get perfect view of the thing."
    new "Most describe it as something between a wolf or a bear, but nobody ever really seems to get perfect view of the thing."

    old "It attacks them out of nowhere, and in their panic, people are more focussed on surviving than remembering the creature."
    new "It attacks them out of nowhere, and in their panic, people are more focussed on surviving than remembering the creature."

    old "Fur, black as ink, though. That's what they all say. And blood-red eyes."
    new "Fur, black as ink, though. That's what they all say. And blood-red eyes."

    old "Sarah frowned, she wasn't sure if that helped any."
    new "Sarah frowned, she wasn't sure if that helped any."

    old "What is being done about it?"
    new "What is being done about it?"

    old "That's the problem."
    new "That's the problem."

    old "This creature, I thought it was an animal. A wild wolf, a frenzied bear, we've dealt with those things before."
    new "This creature, I thought it was an animal. A wild wolf, a frenzied bear, we've dealt with those things before."

    old "We gather up the men and we head out into the forest and hunt it down. It's not easy, but we've done it before."
    new "We gather up the men and we head out into the forest and hunt it down. It's not easy, but we've done it before."

    old "Nine-times, now."
    new "Nine-times, now."

    old "Nine?"
    new "Nine?"

    old "Nine-times we've send hunting groups into the forest."
    new "Nine-times we've send hunting groups into the forest."

    old "Gods, last time we send every last man, even those young lads that can barely be called men, into the forest."
    new "Gods, last time we send every last man, even those young lads that can barely be called men, into the forest."

    old "I said to myself, whatever happens, it ends that night."
    new "I said to myself, whatever happens, it ends that night."

    old "The Beast has no lair to be found. It leaves tracks, but follow them for a while and they vanish."
    new "The Beast has no lair to be found. It leaves tracks, but follow them for a while and they vanish."

    old "Once we thought we had it cornered, and instead, it had somehow snuck past us and fled away again."
    new "Once we thought we had it cornered, and instead, it had somehow snuck past us and fled away again."

    old "So it's hard to catch then."
    new "So it's hard to catch then."

    old "Hard to catch? You're not listening."
    new "Hard to catch? You're not listening."

    old "Wild animals attacks, those are a part of life out here."
    new "Wild animals attacks, those are a part of life out here."

    old "But this thing is like no animal I have ever encountered. It outsmarts us, and it doesn't even seem to kill for food."
    new "But this thing is like no animal I have ever encountered. It outsmarts us, and it doesn't even seem to kill for food."

    old "Sarah frowned as she listened to the Mayor's story."
    new "Sarah frowned as she listened to the Mayor's story."

    old "In the grand scope of all the troubles of the world, it didn't mean much."
    new "In the grand scope of all the troubles of the world, it didn't mean much."

    old "But to see the injury on the girl. The pain in the Mayor's face. It all struck much closer to her."
    new "But to see the injury on the girl. The pain in the Mayor's face. It all struck much closer to her."

    old "What a wicked trouble."
    new "What a wicked trouble."

    old "I wish there was something we could do for you. We can share any medical supplies you might need from our transport wagons."
    new "I wish there was something we could do for you. We can share any medical supplies you might need from our transport wagons."

    old "The Mayor looked up, his eyes bright."
